\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model described in this document is a fully-coupled physical, biogeochemical
, and ecosystem model.
 The generic model framework consists of a physical water column model,
 within which I run a biological module that adds in all the biologically-releva
nt state variables to this physical model.
 I never gave this model (or set of models) a proper name; I have a personal
 aversion to the trend of unintelligible acronyms but nothing better ever
 came to mind.
 I generally refer to it by the names of the Matlab functions it uses: the
 physical model is 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
texttt{mixed
\backslash
_layer.m}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the ecosystem model is 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
texttt{wce.m}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (for water column ecosystem...
 damn, and unpronounceable and uninformative acronym!), and the NPZ-only
 biological module that I use for some setup and comparison is 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
texttt{nemurokak.m}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (my own variant of the popular NEMURO model, with my initials appended).
 Taken as a whole, for the purposes of titling this document, I've just
 named it after myself, since that's how it shows up for citation purposes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Earlier versions of this documentation have appeared as an appendix to my
 Ph.D.
 thesis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kearney2012a"

\end_inset

 and as supplementary material to an earlier journal article 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kearney2013"

\end_inset

.
 Since then, the model has continued to evolve, and likely will continue
 to do so.
 I've spent a lot of time pulling my own hair out in attempts to understand
 the inner workings of other people's models, so I'm trying to keep things
 as transparent as possible with this one.
 This document will likely continue to accompany any publications that use
 this model as supplementary material, since all of this is far too detailed
 to go into journal articles themselves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basic model framework is designed to be generic to any pelagic ocean
 ecosystem.
 But in practice, it requires a huge number of input variables and datasets,
 so its development has been very closely tied to the specifics of my test
 ecosystem, the eastern subarctic gyre of the Pacific Ocean.
 The parameters and input datasets used to run the model for that ecosystem
 are listed here in full.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The physical model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Model framework and equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mixed-layer model simulates the evolution of water column properties
 under specified forcing by wind, heat, and salinity forcing.
 Allowance is also made for currents via a depth-independent pressure accelerati
on.
 There are six physical state variables in the physical model formulation:
 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 are the east to west and south to north current velocities, and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 are the temperature and salinity.
 The turbulence closure scheme introduces the remaining two state variables;
 : 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a turbulent quantity equal to twice the turbulent kinetic energy, and
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 is a turbulent length scale.
 The evolution of these quantities are governed according to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{{\partial U}}{dt}-fV=-\frac{{1}}{\rho_{_{0}}}\frac{{\partial p}}{\partial x}+\frac{\partial}{\partial z}K_{M}\frac{{\partial U}}{\partial z}-\epsilon U\label{eq:dU-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{{\partial V}}{dt}+fU=-\frac{{1}}{\rho_{_{0}}}\frac{{\partial p}}{\partial y}+\frac{\partial}{\partial z}K_{M}\frac{{\partial V}}{\partial z}-\epsilon V\label{eq:dV-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial q^{2}}{\partial t}=\frac{\partial}{\partial z}K_{q}\frac{\partial q^{2}}{\partial z}+2K_{M}\left[\left(\frac{\partial U}{\partial z}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial z}\right)^{2}\right]+\frac{2g}{\rho_{0}}K_{H}\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial z}-\frac{2q^{3}}{B_{1}\ell}\label{eq:dq2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial q^{2}\ell}{\partial t}=\frac{\partial}{\partial z}K_{q}\frac{\partial q^{2}\ell}{\partial z}+E_{1}\ell\left(K_{M}\left[\left(\frac{\partial U}{\partial z}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial z}\right)^{2}\right]+E_{3}\frac{g}{\rho_{0}}K_{H}\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial z}\right)-\frac{q^{3}}{B_{1}}W\label{eq:dq2l}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These equations are solved using a semi-implicit Crank-Nicolson scheme.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Boundary forcing for 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 are set by the wind and bottom stress (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:Wind-forcing"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:Bottom-stress"

\end_inset

).
 The depth-independent pressure acceleration terms is specified as part
 of the model forcing.
 The bottom stress generated by currents arising from this term help prevent
 the bottom layers of the water column from stagnating.
 A dissipation term is included in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:dU-1"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:dV-1"

\end_inset

 as a surrogate for horizontal momentum divergence.
 This term removes energy from past storm events over a specified time-scale
 as though energy was being transferred to more quiescent surrounding waters.
 Energy tends to accumulate unrealistically in 1D water columns without
 this effect 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mellor2001one"

\end_inset

.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 can be tuned such that the energy in the modeled currents is consistent
 with that observed.
 Values comparable to the time scales of storm events (0.2-1 day
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

) seem to yield reasonable results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The turbulent quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}\ell$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:dq2"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:dq2l"

\end_inset

 are used to derive the mixing coefficients for momentum (
\begin_inset Formula $K_{M}$
\end_inset

), turbulence (
\begin_inset Formula $K_{q}$
\end_inset

), and tracers (
\begin_inset Formula $K_{H}$
\end_inset

) using the Mellor-Yamada 2.5 turbulence closure scheme 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mellor1982development"

\end_inset

.
 Terms on the right hand side of these equations represent the transport
 of turbulence, generation of turbulence via shear, and suppression of turbulenc
e via stratification and dissipation.
 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{3}$
\end_inset

 are constants equal to 16.6, 1.8, 1.33 and 1.0, respectively.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is the acceleration due to gravity, and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is a "wall proximity function" which limits the eddy length scale near
 boundaries.
 Further details of the turbulence closure and boundary conditions for the
 turbulent quantities are described below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The temperature and salinity equations are given by: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial T}{\partial t}=\frac{\partial}{\partial z}K_{V}\frac{{\partial T}}{\partial z}+ss\label{eq:dT-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial S}{\partial t}=\frac{\partial}{\partial z}K_{V}\frac{{\partial S}}{\partial z}+ss\label{eq:dS-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:dT-1"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:dS-1"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $ss$
\end_inset

 represents a variety of source and sink terms for temperature and salinity.
 Temperature changes are driven by incident radiation and sensible, latent,
 and longwave heat fluxes.
 A net heat transport via advection can also be specified.
 Salinity changes are presently driven via relaxation to specified values.
 These sources and sinks are described in detail in the sections that follow.
 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 are translated to a density using a routine from Phil Morgan's CSIRO seawater
 toolbox (UNESCO 1983 polynomial).
 Water is modeled as incompressible for this calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Wind forcing
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Wind-forcing"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wind input is provided as u- and v-components of speed in m/s, and translated
 to wind stresses using 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "large1981open"

\end_inset

.
 The stress (N m
\begin_inset Formula $^{-2}$
\end_inset

) is calculated as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau_{x}=\rho_{air}C_{d}|W_{10}|U_{10}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau_{y}=\rho_{air}C_{d}|W_{10}|V_{10}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{10}$
\end_inset

 is the wind speed at 10m, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{d}$
\end_inset

 is a dimensionless drag coefficient, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{air}$
\end_inset

 is the air density (which is assumed to be 1.25 kg m
\begin_inset Formula $^{-3}$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{10}$
\end_inset

 is calculated from the measured wind speed assuming a logarithmic velocity
 profile.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{d}$
\end_inset

 is an empirical function of the wind speed:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C_{d}=\begin{cases}
1.2\times10^{-3} & W_{10}<11\text{ ms}^{-1}\\
1.0\times10^{-3}(0.49+0.065W_{10}) & W_{10}\ge11\text{ ms}^{-1}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
texttt{wstress.m}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 routine from Rich Signell's Matlab toolbox is used for this calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Bottom stresses
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Bottom-stress"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Princeton Ocean Model Formulation from of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mellor2004user"

\end_inset

 is used to calculate the bottom stress:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau_{x,b}=\rho C_{bot}\left(U^{2}+V^{2}\right)^{1/2}U
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau_{y,b}=\rho C_{bot}\left(U^{2}+V^{2}\right)^{1/2}V
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{bot}$
\end_inset

 is a bottom drag coefficient calculated as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C_{bot}=\max\left(\frac{\kappa^{2}}{\ln\left({\frac{0.5dz}{z_{o}b}}\right)},0.0025\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is Von-Karman's constant (0.4, dimensionless), 
\begin_inset Formula $dz$
\end_inset

 is the thickness of the bottom grid cell (m), and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{ob}$
\end_inset

 is a bottom roughness coefficient.
 The basic form of this relationship comes from a logarithmic boundary layer
 solution.
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{ob}$
\end_inset

 is given a value of 0.01 by default, which is indicative of a rather smooth
 boundary.
 The lower 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{bot}$
\end_inset

 limit comes into play only when 
\begin_inset Formula $dz$
\end_inset

 resolution is very large relative to the roughness length scale.
 It was inserted to be consistent with the POM formulation, but can be avoided
 as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $dz/z_{ob}$
\end_inset

 ~ 5000.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The turbulence closure sub-model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vertical mixing is determined using the Mellor-Yamada 2.5 turbulence closure
 scheme 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mellor1982development"

\end_inset

 with adjustments and simplifications described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Galperin1988"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mellor2004user"

\end_inset

.
 Mixing coefficients are derived from the turbulent quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 which are tracked prognostically via 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:dq2"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:dq2l"

\end_inset

.
 The boundary condition for 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}$
\end_inset

 accounts for waves and is taken from equation (10) of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mellor2004wave"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q^{2}(0)=(15.8\alpha_{CB})^{2/3}u_{\tau}^{2}(z=0)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 is the surface "friction velocity" driven by the wind (
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{{\tau_{wind}/\rho_{w}}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{w}$
\end_inset

 is the surface water density).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mellor2004wave"

\end_inset

 suggest using 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{CB}=100$
\end_inset

.
 A minimum value of 0.0001 is applied, which corresponds to a wind ~1 m/s.
 The bottom boundary condition for 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}$
\end_inset

 is calculated from equation 16a of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mellor2004user"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q^{2}(z=z_{bot})=B_{1}^{2/3}u_{\tau}^{2}(z=z_{bot})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\tau}(z=z_{bot})$
\end_inset

 is the bottom friction velocity.
 The length scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 at the surface is from equations 5a and 6a of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mellor2004wave"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ell(z=0)=\kappa z_{w}=\kappa\beta\frac{{u_{tau}^{2}(z=0)}}{g}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is 2.0
\begin_inset Formula $\times10^{5}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is von Karman's constant (0.41).
 The non-zero length scale at the ocean surface reflects the surface wave
 roughness.
 A minimum 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{w}$
\end_inset

 value of 0.02 was imposed.
 This corresponds to waves generated by a wind of 1 m s
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and is meant to mimic the persistence of some wave energy through calm
 periods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 at the bottom boundary was set to 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wall proximity function 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 limits 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 near the boundaries by enhancing the dissipation.
 The formulation used is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1+E_{2}\left(\frac{{\ell}}{\kappa L}\right)^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a constant (1.33) and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is the distance from the surface or the bottom of the water column:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L=\frac{1}{|z|}+\frac{1}{|z_{bot}-z|}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Various wall proximity functions can be found in the literature and model
 codes.
 This one is very similar to those found in various versions of the Princeton
 Ocean Model and was taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Williams2006"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 is limited in stably stratified flows in accordance with eqs.
 (22), (26) and (30) of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Galperin1988"

\end_inset

.
 This is done using the quantity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{H}=\frac{\ell^{2}g}{q^{2}\rho_{0}}\frac{\partial\rho}{\partial z}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is the ratio of potential (
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{{g}}{\rho_{0}}\frac{{\partial\rho}}{\partial z}$
\end_inset

) to kinetic energy (
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{{\ell^{2}}}{q^{2}}$
\end_inset

).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{{\partial\rho}}{\partial z}$
\end_inset

 is negative in stable water columns (i.e.
 z=0 at the water surface and becomes more negative with depth), 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{H}$
\end_inset

 is negative in stable water columns.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Galperin1988"

\end_inset

 found it necessary to limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 in highly stable flows such that stayed below 0.28.
 Minimum values of 1e-9 are imposed on both 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}\ell$
\end_inset

 in accordance with the POM2K code.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The diffusivities are calculated from 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}$
\end_inset

 and following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mellor1982development"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Galperin1988"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{M}=q\ell S_{M}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{H}=q\ell S_{H}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{q}=0.41q\ell S_{H}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The factors 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{H}$
\end_inset

 all depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{H}$
\end_inset

 according to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{H}=\frac{A_{2}\left(1-6\frac{A_{1}}{B_{1}}\right)}{1-(3A_{2}B_{2}-18A_{1}A_{2})G_{H}}\sim\frac{0.49}{1-34.68G_{H}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{2}$
\end_inset

 are empirical constants that are 0.92, 0.74, 16.6, and 10.1, respectively.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{H}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{H}$
\end_inset

 values approaching 0.028 (unstable, high energy conditions), values of 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{H}$
\end_inset

 are capped at 0.028.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{H}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{H}\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset

 (highly stable or low energy conditions).
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{M}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{M}=\frac{A_{1}\left(1-3C_{1}-6\frac{A_{1}}{B_{1}}\right)+S_{H}\left[\left(18A_{1}^{2}+9A_{1}A_{2}\right)G_{H}\right]}{1-9A_{1}A_{2}G_{H}}\sim\frac{0.39+21.36S_{H}G_{H}}{1-6.1G_{H}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

 is 0.08.
 This factor also approaches 0 as 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{H}\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Heat forcing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The heat forcing input calls for the incident flux, air temperature, and
 the dew point temperature.
 Sensible, latent, and longwave fluxes are calculated using various bulk
 formulae described below.
 This has the advantages of relying on commonly measured quantities and
 allowing feedbacks between observed atmosphere conditions and the calculated
 ocean temperature.
 Such feedbacks reduce the probability of developing large, persistent biases
 over long model runs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The incident irradiance (
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

) is entered in watts m
\begin_inset Formula $^{-2}$
\end_inset

 and the model assumes that data represents energy over the wavelength range
 measured by most pyranometers (300-5000 nanometers).
 This is adjusted downward according to the albedo specified in the input
 data.
 45% of the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be from the photosynthetically available range (350-700 nm,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Baker1987"

\end_inset

).
 By default, this energy is assumed to have an attenuation coefficient of
 0.15 m
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 The remaining fraction is attributed to infrared wavelengths and is absorbed
 rapidly (1.67 m
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

).
 Self-shading by phytoplankton is applied within the primary production
 calculations in the ecosystem model but does not feed back to the physical
 state variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "friehe1976parameterization"

\end_inset

 formulae are used to estimate the sensible heat flux (
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{s}$
\end_inset

, watts m
\begin_inset Formula $^{-2}$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{s}=\rho_{air}C_{p}\overline{{\omega\theta}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{air}$
\end_inset

 is the air density (assumed to be ~1.2 kg m
\begin_inset Formula $^{-2}$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}$
\end_inset

 is the specific heat capacity of air (1000 J kg
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 K
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

), and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{{\omega\theta}}$
\end_inset

 is the mean vertical velocity-temperature covariance (m K s
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

).
 This latter term is estimated as a function of wind speed at 10m (
\begin_inset Formula $W_{10}$
\end_inset

) and the sea-air temperature difference (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta T=T_{ocean}-T_{air})$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\omega\theta}=\begin{cases}
0.002+(0.97\times10^{-3})W_{10}\Delta T & 0<W_{10}\Delta T<25\text{ (unstable)}\\
(1.46\times10^{-3})W_{10}\Delta T & W_{10}\Delta T\ge25\text{ (highly unstable)}\\
0.0026+(0.86\times10^{-3})W_{10}\Delta T & W_{10}\Delta T\le0\text{ (stable)}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The sensible heat goes exclusively into the top grid cell.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formulae of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "friehe1976parameterization"

\end_inset

 are also used to estimate the latent heat flux (
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{L}$
\end_inset

, watts m
\begin_inset Formula $^{-2}$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{L}=L_{e}\overline{wq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{wq}$
\end_inset

 is the mean vertical velocity-water vapor density covariance (m s
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 g m
\begin_inset Formula $^{-3}$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{e}$
\end_inset

 is the latent heat of evaporation (2250 J g
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

).
 This is estimated with the formula:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{L}=L_{e}(1.32\times10^{-3})W_{10}(q_{s}-q_{a})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the water vapor density (g m
\begin_inset Formula $^{-3}$
\end_inset

) at the sea surface, and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the water vapor density (g m
\begin_inset Formula $^{-3}$
\end_inset

) at a reference height above the ocean surface (~10m).
 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{s}$
\end_inset

 is calculated as the saturation humidity at the sea surface temperature
 (following the approach used in the Princeton Ocean Model).
 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{a}$
\end_inset

 is determined from the measure dew point temperature in the model forcing.
 The approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{s}=Ae^{\beta T}$
\end_inset

 is used to calculate the saturated vapor pressure at temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 for these calculations, where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 = 611 Pa and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 = 0.067 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\circ}$
\end_inset

C
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 This was taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 6"
key "Marshall2008a"

\end_inset

 and gives of the saturated vapor pressure at typical atmospheric conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The longwave flux (
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{LW}$
\end_inset

) is calculated using the Efimova formula as reported by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "simpson1979mid"

\end_inset

.
 This calculates the clear-sky longwave radiation flux as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{LW,clear}=\varepsilon\sigma T_{srf}^{4}\left(0.254-0.00495e_{a}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 is the emissivity of the surface (0.97), 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the Stefan-Boltzman constant (5.67e-8 W m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

K
\begin_inset Formula $^{-4}$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{srf}$
\end_inset

 is the surface ocean temperature (K), and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the atmospheric vapor pressure (in mb = 100 Pascals).
 The clear sky longwave radiation loss is adjusted downward by a cloud correctio
n factor of the form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{LW}=Q_{LW,clear}(1-0.8C)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is the ratio of the observed incident radiation (
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

) over 24 hours and the clear-sky value estimated using the Smithsonian
 formulas as reported in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Reed1977"

\end_inset

.
 These calculations are done during the model initialization.
 The clear-sky irradiance is calculated as a function of latitude and time
 of year.
 As of the writing of this description, only formulae good for latitudes
 from 20
\begin_inset Formula $^{\circ}$
\end_inset

S-60
\begin_inset Formula $^{\circ}$
\end_inset

N are included.
 The details can be found in the routine 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
texttt{clearsky.m}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A net heat flux due to advection (
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{adv}$
\end_inset

) can also be considered.
 This heat is added as a source/sink term over a depth scale (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

) following the approach of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Umoh1994"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{adv}(z)=Q_{adv,o}\frac{{\exp\left({\frac{{z}}{\delta}}\right)}}{\delta\left(1-\exp\left({-\frac{{h}}{\delta}}\right)\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This assumed that the majority of the depth-integrated heat flux (
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{adv,o}$
\end_inset

) is distributed over the depth scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

, which is effectively an e-folding scale for the heat transport.
 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 in the above expression it the total depth of the water column.
\end_layout

