\begin_layout Standard
A note on subscripts, which are plentiful in this documentation: subscripts
 indicate the index of a functional group to which a given process variable
 or parameter pertains.
 I typically use 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 as this index, and expand to 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 when I need to represent more than one functional group in a single equation.
 Where variables are related to fluxes between groups, they are denoted
 by two subscripts (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ij}$
\end_inset

), with the source group index followed by the sink group index.
 For clarity I often separate multiple subscripts from each other with commas
 (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{NH_{4},NO_{3}}$
\end_inset

 represents a parameter relating to a flux from the 
\begin_inset Formula $NH_{4}$
\end_inset

 state variable to the 
\begin_inset Formula $NO_{3}$
\end_inset

 variable); commas also separate parameter-name subscripts from functional
 group subscripts (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{max,PS}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{max}$
\end_inset

 growth rate parameter associated with the 
\begin_inset Formula $PS$
\end_inset

 state variable).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The values of the various biological state variables are referred to as
 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}$
\end_inset

 in all the equations below; depending on the particular state variable,
 these can be thought of as either biomass values or nutrient concentrations.
 All phytoplankton groups are represented by three state variables: phytoplankto
n nitrogen (
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}$
\end_inset

), phytoplankton silica (
\begin_inset Formula $B_{Si,i}$
\end_inset

), and phytoplankton iron (
\begin_inset Formula $B_{Fe,i}$
\end_inset

), while zooplankton and nekton groups consist of only nitrogen state variables.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gross Primary Production (Gpp)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gross primary production fluxes flow from the 
\begin_inset Formula $NO_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $NH_{4}$
\end_inset

 variables to each phytoplankton group, following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kishi2007a"

\end_inset

, with the addition of iron limitation.
 The uptake of nitrogen is described by: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Gpp_{i}=V_{max,i}\exp({K_{gpp,i}T})\cdot L_{nut,i}\cdot L_{light,i}\cdot B_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the nitrogen-based biomass of group 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, resolved with depth.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:nemparamgpp"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:wcenemDerivedParams"

\end_inset

 for parameter values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Respiration (Res)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Respiration applies to all phytoplankton groups, and flows from the phytoplankto
n to the 
\begin_inset Formula $NO_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $NH_{4}$
\end_inset

 groups following the same f-ratio as uptake via primary production: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Res_{i}=Res_{0i}\exp({K_{res,i}T})B_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:nemparamres"

\end_inset

 for parameter values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Extracellular excretion (Ex)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Extracellular excretion applies to all phytoplankton groups, and flows from
 the phytoplankton to the 
\begin_inset Formula $DON$
\end_inset

 group.
 Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kishi2007a"

\end_inset

, extracellular excretion is proportional to the flux due to gross primary
 production:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Ex_{i}=\gamma_{i}\cdot Gpp{}_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:nemparamexx"

\end_inset

 for parameter values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Consumption (Con)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Predator/prey interactions between functional groups follow the Aydin version
 of the foraging arena functional response.
 The exact form of the functional response varies based on whether the predator
 and prey groups are planktonic or nektonic.
 For interactions between two planktonic groups, the flux (referred to as
 grazing in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:circleflux"

\end_inset

) is resolved with depth for both the predator and prey group, and the uptake
 rates are temperature-dependent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Con_{ij}=\frac{{Q'_{ij}}}{\exp(K_{Gra,i}\cdot T_{avg})}\exp(K_{Gra,i}\cdot T)\left(\frac{X_{ij}\cdot\frac{{B_{j}}}{B'_{j}}}{X_{ij}-1+\frac{{B_{j}}}{B'_{j}}}\right)\left(\frac{D_{ij}\cdot\left(\frac{{B_{i}}}{B'_{i}}\right)^{\theta_{ij}}}{D_{ij}-1+\left(\frac{{B_{i}}}{B'_{i}}\right)^{\theta_{ij}}}\right)\label{eq:plankCon}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where here, the subscripts 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 represent the prey and predator groups, respectively.
 The biomass and consumption rate parameters are derived from the Ecopath
 mass balance: 
\begin_inset Formula $Q'=\frac{{Q^{*}}}{MLD}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B'=\frac{{B^{*}}}{MLD}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{*}$
\end_inset

 are the per-area mass-balanced quantities returned directly from Ecopath.
 The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $MLD$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{avg}$
\end_inset

 describe the yearly averaged mixed layer depth and mixed layer temperature,
 respectively, as simulated by the one-dimensional physical model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For interactions between two nektonic groups, the functional response follows
 the same form, but in units of biomass integrated over depth (termed predation
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:circleflux"

\end_inset

)
\series bold
.
 
\series default
For shorthand,
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $Bint$
\end_inset


\series default
 is used for depth-integrated biomass.
 Nektonic consumption does not vary with temperature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Con_{ij}=Q_{ij}^{*}\left(\frac{X_{ij}\cdot\frac{{Bint_{j}}}{B_{j}^{*}}}{X_{ij}-1+\frac{{Bint_{j}}}{B_{j}^{*}}}\right)\left(\frac{D_{ij}\cdot\left(\frac{{Bint_{i}}}{B_{i}^{*}}\right)^{\theta_{ij}}}{D_{ij}-1+\left(\frac{{Bint_{i}}}{B_{i}^{*}}\right)^{\theta_{ij}}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a nektonic group preys upon a planktonic group, the total flux is calculate
d in depth-integrated units.
 However, the loss on the plankton side is resolved with depth and distributed
 proportionally to the prey biomass at each depth (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:preZoo"

\end_inset

), while the flow to the predator remains in depth-integrated units (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:preNek"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Con_{ij}=Q_{ij}^{*}\left(\frac{X_{ij}\cdot\frac{{Bint_{j}}}{B_{j}^{*}}}{X_{ij}-1+\frac{{Bint_{j}}}{B_{j}^{*}}}\right)\left(\frac{D_{ij}\cdot\left(\frac{{\int_{0}^{z_{max}}B_{i}dz}}{B_{i}^{*}}\right)^{\theta_{ij}}}{D_{ij}-1+\left(\frac{{\int_{0}^{z_{max}}B_{i}dz}}{B_{i}^{*}}\right)^{\theta_{ij}}}\right)\cdot\frac{1}{\Delta z}\cdot\frac{B_{i}\Delta z}{\int_{0}^{z_{max}}{B_{i}}dz}\label{eq:preZoo}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
ConI_{ij}=Q_{ij}^{*}\left(\frac{X_{ij}\cdot\frac{{Bint_{j}}}{B_{j}^{*}}}{X_{ij}-1+\frac{{Bint_{j}}}{B_{j}^{*}}}\right)\left(\frac{D_{ij}\cdot\left(\frac{{Bint_{i}}}{B_{i}^{*}}\right)^{\theta_{ij}}}{D_{ij}-1+\left(\frac{{Bint_{i}}}{B_{i}^{*}}\right)^{\theta_{ij}}}\right)\label{eq:preNek}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the most recent version of the model code, an additional parameter is
 assigned to each predator, indicating prey visibility (as a fraction from
 0-1) versus depth.
 It is used to adjust 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Bint_{i}$
\end_inset

 values to each predator based on the foraging/hunting behavior of the predator.
 This allows us to, for example, limit nektonic predation to only the upper
 portion of the water column for pelagic species.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:nemparamgra"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:ecopathderivedState"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:ecopathderivedLink"

\end_inset

 for parameter values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Excretion (Exc) and egestion (Ege)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Egestion and excretion are proportional to the total consumption of prey
 by a predator.
 Egestion flows from the predator to the 
\begin_inset Formula $PON$
\end_inset

 group.
 Excretion flows from the predator group to the 
\begin_inset Formula $NH_{4}$
\end_inset

 group.
 All excretion and egestion by nektonic groups is assumed to take place
 in the surface layer:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Ege_{i}= & GS_{i}\cdot\left(\sum_{k=plank}{Con_{ki}}+\frac{\sum_{\ell=nek}{ConI_{\ell i}}}{\Delta z_{1}}\right) & z=1\\
Ege_{i}= & GS_{i}\cdot\sum_{k}{Con_{ki}} & z\neq1\\
Exc_{i}= & \left(1-GE_{i}-GS_{i}\right)\cdot\left(\sum_{k=plank}{Con_{ki}}+\frac{\sum_{\ell=nek}{ConI_{\ell i}}}{\Delta z_{1}}\right) & z=1\\
Exc_{i}= & (1-GE_{i}-GS_{i})\cdot\sum_{k}{Con_{ki}} & z\neq1
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:ecopathderivedState"

\end_inset

 for parameter values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Non-predatory mortality (Mor)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-predatory loss process is used to represent the net effect of a
 diversity of loss processes, including natural mortality (i.e.
 death due to old age), loss to disease and viruses, unresolved intra-group
 mortality (such as egg cannibalism and predation on juveniles of similar
 species), aggregation and sinking out of the modeled system (primarily
 of large phytoplankton), and metabolic costs.
 It flows from each living functional group to the 
\begin_inset Formula $PON$
\end_inset

 group, and is allowed to vary in functional form between groups, based
 on the exponent parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 A value of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 leads to linear mortality, while 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}=2$
\end_inset

 indicates a quadratic loss term.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kearney2013"

\end_inset

 for a detailed sensitivity study related to this exponent term.
 For planktonic groups, the non-predatory flux is in units of mass per volume:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Mor_{i}=\left(\frac{M_{0i}}{B_{i}'^{(c_{i}-1)}}\right)\cdot B_{i}^{c_{i}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

while for nektonic groups it is in units of mass per area:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
MorI_{i}=\left(\frac{M_{0i}}{B_{i}^{*(c_{i}-1)}}\right)\cdot Bint_{i}^{c_{i}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As with egestion and excretion by nektonic groups, non-predatory mortality
 of nektonic groups is assumed to occur in the surface layer, such that
 in the surface layer, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Mor_{i}=\frac{{MorI_{i}}}{\Delta z_{1}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

when 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 = nekton.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:nemparammor"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:ecopathderivedState"

\end_inset

 for parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Proportional-to-nitrogen fluxes of silica and iron
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The majority of fluxes between iron- and silica-based state variables occur
 in proportion to nitrogenous fluxes.
 Silica fluxes due to gross primary production (
\begin_inset Formula $Gpp$
\end_inset

), extracellular excretion (
\begin_inset Formula $Ex$
\end_inset

), and respiration (
\begin_inset Formula $Res$
\end_inset

) between phytoplankton groups and 
\begin_inset Formula $SiOH_{4}$
\end_inset

 occur in a constant proportion to the respective fluxes in nitrogen between
 phytoplankton groups and all dissolved nitrogen pools (
\begin_inset Formula $NO_{3}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $NH_{4}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $DON$
\end_inset

).
 Similarly, fluxes due to non-predatory mortality (
\begin_inset Formula $Mor$
\end_inset

) from phytoplankton groups to the 
\begin_inset Formula $PON$
\end_inset

 group are accompanied by proportional fluxes of silica from the large phytoplan
kton to particulate opal group.
 Silica is assumed to be completely egested by phytoplankton grazers, so
 the proportional flux due to predator consumption (
\begin_inset Formula $Con$
\end_inset

) of phytoplankton silica is routed entirely to the particulate opal group,
 rather than being split between predator, egestion, and excretion as is
 the case for nitrogenous consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Iron fluxes between the two phytoplankton groups and the dissolved and particula
te iron groups also occur proportionally to nitrogen fluxes, though the
 ratio between the two elements varies over time (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:Iron-uptake-(Qup)"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Decomposition (Dec)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decomposition fluxes follow the model of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kishi2007a"

\end_inset

, with a decay rate related to temperature:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Dec_{ij}=V_{Dec,ij}\exp(K_{Dec,ij}T)\cdot B_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the subscripts 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 represent the source and sink groups, respectively, and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}$
\end_inset

 the concentration of the source group.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:nemparamdec"

\end_inset

 for parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Iron uptake (Qup)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Iron-uptake-(Qup)"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This iron model is based closely on one developed for the Carbon, Ocean
 Biogeochemistry and Lower Trophics (COBALT) marine ecosystem model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Stock"

\end_inset

, with a few adjustments to parameter values in order to tune the dynamics
 to a one-dimensional water column.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Iron uptake, flowing from the 
\begin_inset Formula $Fe$
\end_inset

 group to each phytoplankton group, is based on an internal cell quota of
 the phytoplankton, accounting for both requirements and additional luxury
 uptake.
 Iron's contribution to overall nutrient limitation, which regulates the
 uptake of macronutrients, is termed iron deficiency (
\begin_inset Formula $D_{Fe,i}$
\end_inset

) and is calculated based on the internal ratio of iron to nitrogen.
 However, uptake of iron is not proportional to uptake of nitrogen, but
 instead based on a separate limitation term (
\begin_inset Formula $L_{Fe,i}$
\end_inset

), allowing phytoplankton to increase their internal Fe:N ratios to a preset
 limit:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Qup_{i}=\begin{cases}
V_{max,i}\exp({K_{gpp,i}T})\cdot B_{Fe,i}\cdot L_{Fe,i}\cdot\mu_{Fe:N,i}, & \text{if }R_{Fe:N,i}<R_{Fe:Nmax,i}\\
0, & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Iron is not tracked beyond the level of phytoplankton, but upon loss to
 predation is recycled to the dissolved and particulate iron state variables
 proportionate to the nitrogenous excretion and egestion fluxes of their
 predators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:nemparamquo"

\end_inset

 for parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Iron scavenging (Ads)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scavenging of dissolved iron onto particles (
\begin_inset Formula $Fe$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $POFe$
\end_inset

) follows a single ligand model, where only non-ligand-bound iron is available
 for adsorption onto particles.
 Light is assumed to greatly reduce the effectiveness of ligand binding
 through the production of oxygen free radicals 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fan2008"

\end_inset

.
 This impact is assumed to decay at light levels below 10 W m
\begin_inset Formula $-^{2}$
\end_inset

 in a manner consistent with the observed decline of hydrogen peroxide in
 the water column 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Yuan2001"

\end_inset

.
 The free unbound iron, 
\begin_inset Formula $Fe_{free}$
\end_inset

, is calculated via:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{Lig}\cdot Fe_{free}^{2}+\left(1+K_{Lig}\cdot(Lig_{bkg}-Fe)\right)\cdot Fe_{free}-B_{Fe}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Adsorption onto particles is directly proportional to this free iron.
 Iron scavenging rates have been observed to be lower above dissolved iron
 concentrations of 0.6 nM, possibly due to less complexation with ligands
 at these concentrations
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Johnson1997"

\end_inset

, so the final scavenging equations allow for this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Ads=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
\alpha_{scav}\cdot Fe_{free} & \quad\text{\ensuremath{Fe_{free}\leq}0.6}\\
0.08\cdot(Fe_{free}-0.6)\cdot\alpha_{scav}\cdot Fe_{free} & \quad\text{\ensuremath{Fe_{free}>}0.6}
\end{array}\right.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, a fraction of particulate iron is remineralized to the dissolved
 iron pool, proportional to remineralization of particulate nitrogen to
 ammonium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Dec_{POFe,Fe}=Dec_{PON,NH_{4}}\cdot\frac{B_{PON}}{B_{POFe}}\cdot r_{eff}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:nemparamquo"

\end_inset

 for parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Rerouting of fluxes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By default, the flux processes move biomass from specific source and sink
 groups as described in the sections above.
 But they can also be redirected in order to tune the model a bit to specific
 behaviors of individual functional groups.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Eastern Subarctic Gyre ecosystem model, the following rerouting adjustmen
ts were made:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Small phytoplankton non-predatory mortality: 25% is redirected to 
\begin_inset Formula $DON$
\end_inset

 and 25% is redirected to 
\begin_inset Formula $NH_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 The small size of this group means that their loss contributes little to
 the heavy, sinking particles of the 
\begin_inset Formula $PON$
\end_inset

 group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Microzooplankton egestion: 25% is redirected to 
\begin_inset Formula $DON$
\end_inset

 and 25% is redirected to 
\begin_inset Formula $NH_{4}$
\end_inset

.
 They prey on small phytoplankton, and again, this flux behaves more like
 dissolved material than sinking particulates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Non-predatory mortality of birds, mammals, and sharks (albatross, sperm
 whales, toothed whales, elephant seals, seals/dolphins, fulmars, skuas/jaegers,
 puffins/shearwaters/storm petrels, kittiwakes, sharks): 90% redirected
 out of the system.
 Loss of these groups typically occur outside of the modeled system, either
 out of the water or sinking quickly to deep water, and therefore little
 of their biomass is recycled to the nutrient pools of the modeled system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Non-predatory mortality of fisheries target species (pomfret, chum salmon,
 chinook/coho/steelhead, sockeye/pink, saury, sergestid shrimp): 90% is
 redirected to fishing loss.
 Our initial Ecopath model does not explicitly resolve fisheries loss, instead
 including this loss with other non-predatory losses.
 This redirection removes these losses from the flux back into the nutrient
 pools, and allows us to quantify a rough estimate of fisheries landings.
\end_layout

