\begin_layout Subsubsection
Ensemble generation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The construction of a typical Ecopath model involves the compilation of
 a large amount of population-related data, including biomass, production
 rates, consumption rates, diet fractions, growth efficiencies, and assimilation
 efficiencies for each functional group included in the model.
 These data typically come from a wide variety of sources, ranging from
 high-quality scientific surveys to fisheries landing data, empirical relationsh
ips, and other models.
 The uncertainty values on these numbers can be very high, up to or beyond
 an order of magnitude from the point estimates, and accurate measurement
 of these uncertainties is rare.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the inclusion of pedigree values, i.e.
 estimates of the quality of each parameter based on its underlying source,
 is relatively common when documenting Ecopath models, the uncertainty informati
on is rarely incorporated into the predicted results deriving from these
 models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "eweusersguide"

\end_inset

.
 However, the wide range of uncertainty associated with some input values
 means that often a single simulation based on the mean inputs does not
 capture the true range of possible outcomes; in some cases even the direction
 of change in one functional group as a result of a perturbation to a different
 group cannot be fully ascertained when accounting for the entire input
 range.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In previous work, when coupling an Ecopath-derived predator/prey model to
 a seasonally-varying biogeochemical model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kearney2012,Kearney2013"

\end_inset

, we found that small numerical differences in initial parameters could
 occasionally lead to outlier-type results.
 Rather than constantly readjusting the hundreds of parameters to find a
 single set of perfectly-tuned numbers that were both representative of
 the entire ecosystem and numerically well-behaved, we instead decided to
 use an ensemble of Ecopath models to derive our parameters and thereby
 encompass as much of the potential parameter space as possible.
 The process is as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Step 1: For each user-input parameter in the model, choose 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 random values based on the prescribed probability density functions for
 each parameter.
 
\emph default
Currently, the code allows uncertainty to be applied to biomass (
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i}$
\end_inset

), production per unit biomass (
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{{P}}{B}_{i}$
\end_inset

), consumption per unit biomass (
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{{Q}}{B}_{i}$
\end_inset

), ecotrophic efficiency (
\begin_inset Formula $EE_{i}$
\end_inset

), growth efficiency (
\begin_inset Formula $GE_{i}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{{P}}{Q}_{i}$
\end_inset

), and each component of the diet composition (
\begin_inset Formula $DC_{ij}$
\end_inset

).
 Each parameter is assigned a lognormal distribution function with mean
 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{{mp}}{2}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the initial point estimate for the parameter and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the respective pedigree value; in terms of the lognormal probability
 density function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(x,\mu,\sigma)=\frac{1}{x\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-\frac{(\ln{x}-\mu)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

this leads to values of
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu=\ln\left({\frac{m^{2}}{\sqrt{\left(\frac{mp}{2}\right)^{2}+m^{2}}}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma=\sqrt{\ln{\left(\frac{p^{2}}{4}+1\right)}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lognormal distribution was chosen so that the resulting values would
 always remain non-negative without the need for hard limits on the parameter
 ranges.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remaining input variables, including assimilation efficiencies (
\begin_inset Formula $GS_{i}$
\end_inset

), fishing loss due to landings and discards (
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

), biomass accumulation (
\begin_inset Formula $BA_{i}$
\end_inset

), and net migration due to immigration and emigration (
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}$
\end_inset

) remain as point estimates.
 In theory, the technique could easily be extended to include these parameters
 as well, but pedigree analyses tend to ignore these, likely for a variety
 of reasons (
\begin_inset Formula $BA_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}$
\end_inset

 are typically non-zero for only a small number of groups in a model; 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{i}$
\end_inset

 only applies to fished species; 
\begin_inset Formula $GS_{i}$
\end_inset

 is rarely modified from its default value of 0.2-0.3).
