\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Step 2: Substitute each set of parameters into the Ecopath model, and make
 the necessary adjustments to diet composition and multi-stanza group biomass
 and consumption rates.
 
\emph default
Some of the parameters in an Ecopath model must by definition covary with
 other input variables.
 First, diet composition components for a single predator must sum to 1.
 This normalization of diet will result in the final set of 
\begin_inset Formula $DC$
\end_inset

 components falling along a normal distribution rather than lognormal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multi-stanza groups also require special treatment at this point.
 In an Ecopath model, biomass groups can represent different life history
 stages of the same functional group.
 Ecopath assumes that multi-stanza functional groups represent a stable
 age-size distribution, and that body size (and by extension biomass and
 consumption rates) follow a von Bertalanffy growth curve 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "christensen2004"

\end_inset

.
 The stable age assumption implies that the survivorship 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{a}$
\end_inset

 at age 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a function of mortality rates (note that in Ecopath, mortality rate
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{i}$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be equal to production rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{{P}}{B}_{i}$
\end_inset

) and biomass accumulation rate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
l_{a}=\exp\left({-\int_{0}^{a}{Z_{a}}-a\frac{BA_{i}}{B_{i}}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the von Bertalanffy assumption states that weight 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{a}$
\end_inset

 is related to age by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{a}=(1-\exp(-K_{i}a))^{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and that consumption is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{a}^{2/3}$
\end_inset

; the growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{i}$
\end_inset

 is provided as input by the user for all multi-stanza groups in Ecopath.
 Based on these assumptions, the proportion of biomass at age 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b_{a}=\frac{l_{a}w_{a}}{\int_{0}^{a_{max}}l_{a}w_{a}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and by extension, the proportion of biomass within a stanza defined between
 ages 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{smin}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{smax}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b_{s}=\frac{\int_{a_{smin}}^{a_{smax}}l_{a}w_{a}}{\int_{0}^{a_{max}}l_{a}w_{a}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Likewise, consumption within a stanza is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{s}=\frac{\int_{a_{smin}}^{a_{smax}}l_{a}w_{a}^{2/3}}{\int_{0}^{a_{max}}l_{a}w_{a}^{2/3}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, biomass and consumption rates are only set for a single leading
 stanza group, typically the oldest group, and values for the other stanzas
 are calculated such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B_{tot}=\frac{B_{s=\textrm{lead}}}{b_{s=\textrm{lead}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B_{s}=B_{tot}b_{s}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{tot}=\frac{B_{s=\textrm{lead}}\frac{Q}{B}_{s=\textrm{lead}}}{q_{s=\textrm{lead}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{Q}{B}\right)_{s}=\frac{Q_{tot}q_{s}}{B_{s}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Step 3: Calculate ecotrophic efficiency values for each of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 Ecopath models.
 Keep only the models that satisfy the mass balance criteria.

\emph default
 Balance within an Ecopath model is diagnosed via the ecotrophic efficiency
 (EE) values for each group, defined as the fraction of net group production
 that is passed up the food chain to predators.
 An ecotrophic efficiency value outside the range of 0-1 implies that the
 system requires an outside sink or source in order to account for all biomass
 fluxes, and results when input data contradict each other (for example,
 a predator has a consumption rate that cannot be sustained by the known
 biomass of its prey).
 At this point, we keep only the parameter sets that result in a balanced
 model.
 For most Ecopath models, this will only be a small fraction of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Step 4: Repeat steps 1-3 until 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 balanced models have been created.

\emph default
 By repeating the process of sampling parameters, testing for balance, and
 keeping only those models that satisfied the balance criteria, we are able
 to construct an ensemble of Ecopath food web models that incorporate the
 potential measurement uncertainty.
\end_layout

